# Angular component structure

Each component lives in its own folder with separate template and class files.

## Required layout

```
app-feature-name/
  app-feature-name.ts      # @Component class only
  app-feature-name.html    # template
```

Route-level pages may omit the `app-` folder prefix (e.g. `home/home.ts` → selector `app-home`).

## Rules

- Use `templateUrl: './app-feature-name.html'` — never inline `template: \`...\``.
- One `@Component` per `.ts` file. Do not combine multiple components in one file.
- Shared types go in a dedicated `*.types.ts` file (e.g. `item-sheet.types.ts`), not in a component file.
- **Folder name = file name = selector = HTML tag** (e.g. `app-item-section/` → `app-item-section.ts` → selector `app-item-section` → `<app-item-section>`). This makes tag-to-file navigation work in the IDE.

## Examples

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — folder item-section/ but selector app-item-section
@Component({ selector: 'app-item-section', templateUrl: './item-section.html' })

// ✅ GOOD
@Component({
  selector: 'app-item-section',
  standalone: true,
  templateUrl: './app-item-section.html',
})
export class ItemSectionComponent {}
```

```html
<!-- ✅ GOOD — tag matches folder app-item-section/ -->
<app-item-section [items]="items()" titleKey="ITEMS.SECTION_TO_BUY" />
```
